As we get into working with github (that will be the out-of-class reading between Thursday’s class and next Tuesday’s class), Kristen and I will show you how to pull those files from github down to your computer, or “local environment”. If you are interested in playing with Atom before then, you can try the following:
1. click on the green “Clone or Download” button (see image below)
2. click the “Download ZIP” option (for those of you who haven’t worked with a ZIP file before, it is simply a way of bundling together files and compressing them in an “archive", which makes it easier to transfer them as a group)
3. locate the downloaded files and unzip them (that should involve just double-clicking on the archive file)
4. open the .html file in Atom and play with it—make changes, break it, fix it, etc.—and then save it
5. open the .html file in Chrome to see how your changes look in the browser

I strongly encourage you to create a folder on your computer where you keep all the files and exercises we work on in this course. You might call it “workspace” or something like that. If you do so, you will want to move the unzipped folder from your Downloads folder to your “workspace” folder after Step 3. Please let me know if you have any questions or difficulties in following these instructions!

messages.text: Hi, everyone! It was great meeting you all last night and I’m excited about what we’ll accomplish over the next eight weeks. Here is an article on accessing Chrome’s Dev Tools that you may find useful. All of it is illuminating, but I would suggest focusing on the beginning material—up to and including the section "Working with the Console”:  <https://developer.chrome.com/devtools>
Reminder on how to open Chrome dev tools: ```command + option + i```
<http://workshops.galvanize.com/#/>
